article.description: San Diego State 74, Long Beach State 44
article.headline: San Diego State 74, Long Beach State 44
article.linkText: San Diego State 74, Long Beach State 44
article.story: SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Wesley Stokes kept feeding Marcus Slaughter and the freshman kept shooting. Both players made impressive debuts for San Diego State, which routed Long Beach State 74-44 in the season-opener for both teams Friday night. Slaughter scored a game-high 19 points in a reserve role before leaving midway through the second half with a slightly sprained right ankle. Stokes, the point guard who sat out last season after transferring from Missouri, had 17 points and six assists. "Wesley gave me my first pass, actually my first three passes," said Slaughter, who played at J.W. North High in Riverside, Calif. "After that I felt, `Man, I'm hot.' It just went in. "I wasn't looking to do anything spectacular, just whatever came my way," Slaughter said. "Get used to it," Stokes chimed in. Slaughter's 19 points matched the most by a freshman in a season-opener in Steve Fisher's 13 seasons as a head coach. Chris Webber also had 19 for Michigan against Detroit Mercy in 1992. Freshman Brandon Heath, the Aztecs' other starting guard, scored 12 points. San Diego State used an 18-0 run midway through the first half to take a 25-5 lead. Slaughter made three 3-point shots from the baseline during the run and Stokes made another. Stokes' most impressive play came late in the first half when he stole the ball from Kevin Roberts, led a 2-on-1 break and made an alley-oop pass to Slaughter, who made a slam dunk for a 34-11 lead. Forward Kevin Roberts scored 17 for Long Beach before fouling out. The 49ers shot just 21.4 percent in the first half and finished with 29.1 percent. San Diego State shot just 37.9 percent. "Thirty-eight percent shooting usually doesn't win," Fisher said. "Our defensive effort was the reason we did. Especially in the first half I thought we were very smart and forced them out of anything they were trying to do offensively." It took the Aztecs just more than four minutes to make their first field goal. "Once we got into the flow, everything started coming easy," Stokes said. San Diego State opened its fifth season under Fisher. He led the Aztecs to the NIT last year and the school's first Division I postseason victory, following an NCAA appearance in 2002, the school's first in 17 seasons. Long Beach State was 5-22 last season in its first season under coach Larry Reynolds.
